  "features": [
    "Dual-core: Cortex-M4 (64 MHz) + Cortex-M0+ (32 MHz) for radio",
    "Built-in BLE 5.0 and 802.15.4 (Zigbee/Thread)",
    "Native USB 2.0 Full Speed",
    "1MB Flash, 256KB SRAM",
    "Up to 48 GPIOs (QFN68 package)",
    "Dedicated M0+ core handles radio — keyboard code runs uninterrupted on M4",
    "STM32 ecosystem — CubeMX, HAL, familiar toolchain",
    "Low power modes for battery operation",
    "AES-256 hardware encryption"
  ],
  "concerns": [
    "No established keyboard firmware support — requires significant porting effort",
    "QMK BLE support is experimental and not mainlined",
    "More complex than nRF52840 for BLE keyboard implementation",
    "Requires external antenna and matching network",
    "BLE stack is proprietary binary blob from ST (not open-source like Nordic SoftDevice)",
    "More expensive than nRF52840 for equivalent functionality",
    "Very few keyboard projects use this chip",
    "Requires SWD programmer for initial flash"
  ],
  "designNotes": [
    "Interesting for advanced users who want STM32 familiarity with BLE",
    "Dual-core architecture is elegant — M4 for keyboard, M0+ for radio stack",
    "BLE stack is a binary running on M0+ — ST provides it, cannot be modified",
    "802.15.4 support could enable Zigbee/Thread keyboard protocols in future",
    "Not recommended for most keyboard builds — nRF52840 has much better firmware ecosystem",
    "Consider this only if you have specific STM32 expertise and need BLE"
